definition.value: Any aldopentose where the open-chain form has all the hydroxy groups on the same side in the Fischer projection. Occurrs in two enantiomeric forms, D- and L-ribose, of which only the former is found in nature.
A threose where the keto group is at the 2-position with the hydroxy groups at the 3- and 4-positions having threo-stereochemistry.
A heptose with a (potential) ketone group at the 2-position.

The hydrate of 3-(3,4-dihydroxyphenyl)propanoic acid in which the hydrogens alpha- to the carboxyl group are substituted by hydrazinyl and methyl groups (S-configuration). Carbidopa is a dopa decarboxylase inhibitor, so prevents conversion of levodopa to dopamine. It has no antiparkinson activity by itself, but is used in the management of Parkinson's disease to reduce peripheral adverse effects of levodopa.
A deoxyketohexose derivative that is formally obtained from a psicose.
A ketohexose that is the C-3 epimer of fructose.
A ketohexose derivative that is formally obtained from a sorbose.
A ketohexose derivative that is formally obtained from a tagatose.
A ketohexose used as a functional sweetener.
A ketopentose derivative that is formally obtained from ribulose.
A ketopentose derivative that is formally obtained from xyulose.

Organometallic coordination compounds in which one atom of a transition metal such as iron, ruthenium or osmium is bonded to and only to the face of two cyclopentadienyl [eta(5)-(C5H5)] ligands which lie in parallel planes. The term should not be used for analogues having rings other than cyclopentadienyl as ligands.

An organochlorine compound that is 2-(4-chlorobenzyl)pyridine in which one of the benzylic hydrogens is substituted by 2-(dimethylamino)ethoxy group. It is an ethanolamine-type antihistamine, used as its maleate salt for treating hay fever, as well as mild cases of Parkinson's disease.
A deoxyglucose that is glucose in which the hydroxy group at position 6 has been replaced by a hydrogen.
Any deoxygalactose that is deoxygenated at the 6-position.
